element_texts.text:
January 29, 1967
11:00 P.M.
Dear Jack,
I am definitely not going to start this letter wit "Please forgive me for not writing sooner," because it's so commonplace, but the thought is behind the phrase.
Nothing much has been happening around N.S.E. that would cause much controversy, well, nothing that Huntly or Brinkly would have to tell the nation about. Oh wait, Thursday, Mary fainted by the files; while she was resting "Mother Thompson" came barreling out of her office and told us, (Bessie, Bob, Mary, Leon, and myself) to be quite because some people were working. Good old "Mother T" did it again! Had she had any foresight to probe into the situation she wouldn't

(2)
have made such a complete ASS, excuse the expression but its the only one I can think of that fits her so well, of herself. Mary was absolutely furious. Very soon after "Mother T" had said this she went into Mary's office to apologies. Mary, being the marvelous person she is told her she should have known what was going on before she opened her mouth, but then accepted her apology.
Mary fainted, in my arms no less, because she was looking in the files; naturally on the bottom, and just got up to fast. I was setting there changing the labels on the folder and offered her my little stool. But before I could say "Jack Robinson" she was in my arms. Bessie, Bob, and the Director of Editorial Research came to the rescue. I knew she was alright when she started to joke around.
